{"PATHOLOGY": ["seizures", "cognitive impairment", "motor dysfunction"]}

The pathophysiology of condition Y is thought to involve abnormal excitatory neurotransmission, leading to neuronal hyperexcitability and synaptic damage.

{"PATHOLOGY": ["neuronal hyperexcitability", "synaptic damage"]}

Compound X was previously shown to inhibit target protein Z in vitro and in animal models of condition Y. In the current study, we investigated the mechanism of action of compound X using cellular and molecular techniques.

{"PATHOLOGY": []}

We first examined the effect of compound X on the activity of target protein Z in cultured neurons. Our results showed that compound X inhibited the activity of target protein Z in a concentration-dependent manner.

{"PATHOLOGY": []}

We then explored the molecular mechanisms underlying the inhibitory effect of compound X on target protein Z. Our data indicated that compound X binds to a specific site on target protein Z, leading to a conformational change that inhibits its function.

{"PATHOLOGY": []}

Furthermore, we investigated the effect of compound X on synaptic plasticity in condition Y models. Our findings demonstrated that compound X enhances long-term potentiation (LTP), a form of synaptic plasticity that is crucial for learning and memory.

{"PATHOLOGY": ["learning and memory"]}

